node.text:
Here’s a quick and easy Beetroot Latte recipe – because we all need more coffee alternatives in our lives.

Instructions:

- Combine the almond milk, beetroot powder, dates, and vanilla extract in a high-powered blender until smooth and creamy. 

- Pour this mixture straight into a medium-sized saucepan. If your blender isn't very powerful, or if you don't like small fibers to remain in your drink, strain the mixture first while pouring it into the saucepan.

- Place on the stove on medium-high heat and add in a stick of cinnamon. Let the mixture heat up, stirring throughout to prevent burning. Taste test, and if you like it more sweet add up to 1 Tbsp (15 mL) of maple syrup. When it's cooked at a gentle simmer for about 3 minutes, remove the cinnamon stick.

- To a mug, add a shot of espresso (optional), and then pour onto it your beetroot-infused milk. Give it a stir, and enjoy! 

This Beetroot latte will surely keep you up ‘beet’ all day long!

👉Swipe for recipe 🤩 Ohh man this didn't disappoint!
1. Crumble yeast into the flour
2. Mix the milk, vanilla extract and agave syrup and add to the flour
3. Fold in the eggs and knead it for 5 min
4. Work with the slap and fold method for ~10 min until becomes smooth
5. Shape into a ball without breaking the fold layers you just made
6. Place in a floured bowl, score a cross on the top (see my previous video) and leave resting for min 2hrs or preferably overnight
7. Add your butter and working it in by kneading it
8. Work in your fruits or filling
9. Shape it to whatever form you'd prefer and leave it to almost double before adding a small egg and salt wash, top decoration and baking it at 200 ° for 10-15 min and 150 ° for another 15-20 min.

Ingredients:
500g strong white flour
225g cold milk
75g agave syrup
10g salt
25g fresh yeast
125g cubed unsalted butter
3 large eggs (for pastry, ~150g shelled)
1 small egg (for salt wash)
1 tbs vanilla extract
100g fruit

This is the stairway that leads up to the main floor of our home. The lower half of our split level house is my bedroom, a game room, Dad’s workshop and our storage room. Each day now, when I wake up in my room downstairs everything almost seems the same, but once I go up these stairs to where the majority of the bedrooms, the kitchen, and the living room are, there’s a profound silence and emptiness that’s a painful reminder of all I’ve lost recently. In this past year in North Carolina, I lost Dad, I lost Mom, I lost my job, and, like everyone else, I’ve lost so much in-person connection and community due to COVID19. For many years, Mom and I would make a fun back to school photo for my first day teaching or for full time graduate school the past two years. This is my attempt to continue that tradition alone. School starts today at the high school I taught at in San Diego since 2008, but for the first time since then I’m no longer an employee there. It’s a weird year for them with all virtual learning; it’s a weird year for me with no classes to teach. In the spring, I resigned my teaching position to stay and care for Mom, and I will never regret that decision because there was no way I could leave Mom while she battled ovarian cancer at home during a worldwide pandemic. Her death in June was earlier than we hoped, but Mom made sure I would be taken care of regardless — she was even looking out for me in her final days. She and I agreed that whatever happened I would stay in our family home, work with my brother to wrap up our parents’ estate and their belongings of 56 years of marriage, then I would hopefully return to teach in San Diego next school year. So, that’s the plan. I didn’t know I’d be here alone for a full year. I didn’t know as a country we’d all still be socially distant for so much longer. And, before this past spring, I never imagined I would live alone in this house my parents built more than 25 years ago and filled with love. There’s a lot of sadness here now, but there are so many joyful memories too. Those memories, the thankfulness I have for these past two years here, and my faith in God are helping me to Never Give Up. 🙏🏽❤️💯

On Friday, we went to a small town, hole in the wall, Wisconsin bar. Under the impression that we  would just stay for a few drinks, I agreed to go. I like to have fun, and I sure as hell wasnt going to be deemed the sober party pooper. As drinking goes, one drink led to two, which lead to three, which led to 5 hours (5 SOBER HOURS) at the bar. 
I could go into detail about how sad I felt for all the drunks too inebriated to hold their head up, the drug deals I saw, or how concerned I was about everyone getting home safely, but I'll save that for a different post.
I'm learning so much through this year of "firsts". This weekend, I learned a little more about my boundaries. Never again will I be too afraid to wear the party pooper crown and say when its time to leave. Strangely enough, I never had a craving for a drink. Maybe it was the poor excuse of bar patrons that I felt more sorrow for than envy? Sounds judgemental but I remember being there less than a year ago, so I am saying it from a "takes one to know one" perspective. 
No real reason for this post other than to share real parts from my journey. I am happy to report two things. I remained sober through the miserable bar scene and I spent the remainder of my weekend in the great outdoors. Biking, walking, four wheeling, and spending time with people that make me feel more whole than alcohol ever did. So here's a picture I took that reminds me how thankful I am for another day of sobriety.

3 ВАЖНЫХ СОСТАВЛЯЮЩИХ БЕЗУПРЕЧНОГО СТИЛЯ

Парижский безупречный стиль, о котором так часто говорят, на самом деле можно сложить из трёх важных составляющих. И это три больших блока, о которых я планирую говорить часто, долго и по маленьким порциям  разложить вам для удобного восприятия информации. А пока кратко о каждом:

* Чувство формы
 Вы поймёте геометрию своего тела и какие силуэты, крой, длина подходят именно вам

* Чувство цвета
Также не является врождённым навыком и вы сможете раз и навсегда понять, какие оттенки и их сочетания выигрышно смотрятся на вас вне зависимости от собранных палитр по цветотипу
 
* Чувство собственного стиля
Я покажусь слишком вредной, если скажу, что найти собственный стиль не так уж и просто? 
Дело в том, что собственный стиль приходит с годами и зависит также от внешних факторов. Он складывается из ежедневного выбора, чем себя окружать, в каких местах проводить время и из какой чашки пить чай.

Signature look - тот самый образ, который расскажет о вашем самоощущении языком одежды. На пути к осознанию себя приходит свой стиль.  И ни один стилист не сможет сделать это за вас, кроме как помочь в его поиске: а для этого нужно научиться работать с формой и цветом. 

Начинаем!
